Little children are not always able to understand what they are seeing, and it can remain in the mind and distress, he says.
However, if a child has encountered or heard about the news about refugees on television, it is worth talking about.
It is good to discuss the child’s starting point and listen carefully to what he or she is asking.
The child’s fears may be surprising.
They are not necessarily the ones that the parent thinks he is afraid of.
The child should not be intimidated in vain, even if he is harassed and frightened.
A small child follows closely the behavior of their parents.
If the parents themselves remain calm during the conversation, the child will also feel safe.
Older children are likely to encounter a conversation about refugees at school, with friends or online.
Parents should discuss the matter with them if they think about the child.
The fact is that not all people in the world are doing well.
Parents, together with children, can think about how we feel about this in our family.
Is the world, after all, a safe or unsafe place?
Parents may also have different upbringing perspectives - some may want to protect their children from anxiety whenever possible.
On the other hand: If the family also talks about difficult things, the child will get a model of how to deal with the difficulties that arise in life.
