Inflation in the euro area fell to 0.1% in August
Consumer prices in the euro area rose only marginally in August, i.e. 0.1 per cent year-on-year, Eurostat said today.
The rise in prices was driven down by lower energy prices.
In this way, Eurostat revised its forecast of 0.2 % a few weeks ago slightly downwards.
In July, the inflation rate was 0.2 per cent.
The so-called base inflation fell to 0.9 per cent in August from 1.0 per cent in July.
Eurostat's forecast for underlying inflation was 1.0 %.
Energy in the euro area was 7.2 per cent cheaper last month than a year ago.
Across the EU-28, the average inflation rate was zero in August.
In July, the increase was 0.1 per cent.
Consumer prices rose most from the euro area, or 1.4 per cent, in Malta in August.
In Cyprus, inflation was 1.9 per cent at the lowest prices.
In Finland, inflation was 0.2 per cent negative, according to the EU harmonised price index.
Inflation in the euro area remains persistently far from the European Central Bank (ECB) target, which is a 2% rise in prices over the medium term.
The ECB forecasts an average inflation rate of 0.1% for the euro area this year.
Next year, the increase will pick up to 1.1%, the central bank predicts in its new inflation forecasts announced at the beginning of September.
