This week, the governors of the US Central Bank will sit around a huge mahogany table for two days at a long-awaited meeting to decide whether it is time to raise the steering rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-storey meeting room is a wall painting of the United States.
The map is a reminder that the financial interests of the nation must be put ahead of everything else by the President of the Central Bank, Janet L. Yellen, and his colleagues.
The Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank: they must maximise U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Depression, the governors of the Central Bank have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: economic stability.
It is precisely this third requirement that can be a decisive factor in the decision to be published on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted. The decision whether the U.S. economy is prepared to be weaned from a record-breaking incentive that has been brought about by the short-term interest rate almost zero since the end of 2008 .
While most of the data show a steady growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made the central bank officials already on guard more concerned about increasing instability, and fearing what would happen if the federal fund rate were raised by even a quarter of a percentage point.
"Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important factors to follow," says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economic expert at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“I believe, however, that if they are looking for justification for maintaining interest rates, increased uncertainty in the world market is a valid enough reason to wait,” he says.
No agreement has been reached on the Central Bank's decision, which is already causing nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent study by Bloomberg, about half of financial experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as according to the key indicator, the potential for growth is only about 30%.
This refers to the decline in securities markets if the central bank raises the level, unless the decision-makers succeed in softening the attack by promising that the next draw will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average Index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to 16,599.85.
The recovery was accompanied by the expectation that the central bank would keep the level unchanged this week, says John Lonski, chief economic expert at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,” he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they must make a lot of effort in their policy to support the financial markets so that they do not panic.”
Other experts argue that the increased level would calm the financial markets as it would remove uncertainty as to when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has said in spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that liberals demand more economic development in their complaints.
While job creation slowed down in August, growth in the labour market has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1 per cent, which is the lowest figure in seven years and close to the level that the central bank considers to be the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of recovery.
While inflation is still below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, central bank policymakers say the main reason for this is the temporary impact of the significantly reduced oil price.
The economy "is clear of even higher interest rates and also needs them, given the tightness of the labour market", says Ian Shepherdson, chief economic expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, the financial markets around the world shook last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average Index fell by as much as 16% from its May record, as investors feared China would slow down global growth as well.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now almost 10% below the peak in May.
For central bank decision-makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation, which indicates that interest rates should be raised.
“Without these financial market events and recent weeks’ news of the weakness of China’s economy, policy makers would tighten the level at this meeting,” says Stephen D. Oliner, UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate Special Investigator and former central bank official.
Now he predicts that decision-makers will wait at least a month to gain a better understanding of the effects.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still quite unclear, and they have little information at their disposal as to the consequences of the events in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
In 2013, the suggestion of the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, that the central bank could "decreas" the increase in the amount of money, caused a revolution in the market around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” says Zachary Karabell, Head of Global Strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, said this month that “the central bank has previously overreacted to financial market movements that seem to be separate from the fundamentals of the economy.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in the interest rate, and Lacker, a member of the Committee entitled to vote, refers to the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the Central Bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points during the three meetings “despite its limited, identifiable impact on U.S. economic growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Central Bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should give priority to economic stability only during a major crisis, such as the collapse of the market in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The latest turmoil does not come close to its level, Posen says.
“No one wants a situation where interest rate increases are feared because the market is upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention economic stability; as long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
