Weight loss surgery can help people with mildly obese diabetes
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for people with mildly obese type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these slightly obese diabetics live longer after a weight loss operation than those treated in other ways than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get mortality data," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery expert who wrote the editorial for a new study in the JAMA Surgery magazine.
In bariatric surgery, various methods are used to reduce the size of the abdominal cavity.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but the majority of the subjects in the study have been morbidly obese and have had a BMI of 35 or more.
BMI, or weight-to-length ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is over 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if the person is over 30, they are considered to be obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, with medicinal treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of the cut subjects decreased from 31 to 24,5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI remained roughly the same in 29 people treated by means other than surgery.
Thirty-six per cent of the cut-off people had a complete and 28 per cent partial improvement in their diabetes.
For comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes improved completely by only 1% and in part by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and the “bad” LDL-cholesterol “were generally better in the surgery group,” the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients’ blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect long-term blood sugar levels.
Haemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, the A1c level of hemoglobin dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the treatment group, it remained stable at around 8%.
This improved “glycemic control” as described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, however, did not reduce mortality over the course of five years, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The study group also compared the mean results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared with the gastric reduction surgery group, the gastric bypass surgery group had increased weight loss (18.7 and 14.2 kg), decreased body mass index more (7.4 and 5.1), decreased haemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 and 2.1%), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission by 16.7 per cent and 16.9 per cent (46 per cent, respectively).
The University of Arizona’s College of Medicine-Phoenix’s Blackstone says that while research doesn’t show survival or surgery after five years, there are research findings from Sweden, where surgery led to a longer life in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who had undergone weight loss surgery had a 29 percent lower chance of dying in a 15-year period compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study does not show any improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says the results are encouraging for people with BMI less than 35 who are interested in surgery.
“The results of the study are crucial in that they show that the surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group,” he says, without the risk of an increased risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when the patient has BMI between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ll wait too long before we take this seriously,” he says.
