Xi calls for a wider opening of the economy to the world
The economy needs to be more open to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group on Tuesday to steer the reform.
"China should commit to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of the reform.
“Supporting transparency while driving reforms forward is a new movement and vitality, and creating new space for economic growth,” Xi said.
The Steering Group approved a series of guidelines, including a negative list limiting market access, a relaxation of border inspection principles, a call for state-owned companies to seize private capital, and a revision of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created to identify the sectors and companies that cannot be invested in.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant, as it gives the market a greater role in resource allocation, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more transparent, the statement says.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to manage their business operations.
The opinion also said that China would allow border regions to explore new forms of cross-border economic cooperation as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
More sectors are opening up to private financiers in order to open state-run sectors.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment, and it will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent resident permits of foreigners, "green cards", is facilitated by optimising requirements and simplifying the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guarantee of the professional rights of lawyers and the support of professional judges and prosecutors.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang and senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement released after the meeting.
